english:
  title: A Long Memorial
  author: Choi Chi-won
  language: eng
  text: |-
    I humbly present this memorial. I reflect that a short rope cannot draw from deep wells, and a dull blade cannot pierce what is hardened. Therefore the sage Zhou Ren spoke truly: "When strength fails, one must desist." Each must measure his own capacity and proceed accordingly—how dare I act merely upon desire?

    I am a humble scholar from the Eastern Sea. Years ago I left my home and traveled ten thousand li to study in the Middle Kingdom for a decade. My only aspiration was to pass the examinations and perhaps become a magistrate in the Yangtze valley. Last winter, I resigned my minor post and retreated to the mountains, planning to sit for the Hongci examination, postponing my studies until I might reach the depths of learning like waters reaching the sea. Yet my stipend provided nothing extra, and lacking resources even for paper and ink, I came with broom in hand to sweep before your gate—how could I have imagined that the Grand Commandant would cast his benevolent gaze upon me, granting me position and rank?

    My traces lead to the posting stations, my dwelling beneath eaves that shelter me. I am freed from the poverty of the Eastern Gate, needing only to cultivate the courage of the northern sage. Last midsummer, when you took the field, you called upon me unexpectedly. Though I was granted permission to follow your banner and have long relied upon your vessel, I have ever lamented my own inadequacy—my voice like a cloth drum, my talent like a leaden blade. Though I pour forth all my heart and liver, I cannot match the measure of your intentions. Yet suddenly you regarded my yearning for virtue and my reliance upon benevolence, and specially recommended me for advancement. The Son of Heaven himself responded to your words, and I was elevated beyond all expectation.

    Would this have occurred without the throne's trust in your merit and the empire's adherence to your commands? I rose from a mere county inspector to the Inner Palace secretariat and received the insignia of office. Yet when I observe the radiant officials of this glorious court—men who have served thirty years yet remain in humble blue robes, never advancing to the inner councils—I wonder at my own fortune. How could the nine promotions of the ancients compare to this sudden elevation?

    Once I read in the Analects how Confucius encouraged Qidiao Kai to enter service, and Kai replied, "I have not yet mastered the deeper principles of official life." The Master approved his sincere hesitation. Though I lack Kai's wisdom, I have long admired such steadfast resolve. Recently blessed by your grace with promotion, I immediately submitted a memorial of respectful refusal and returned the official documents you granted. Yet I received your instruction commanding me to accept. Though my sincere remonstrance was not heeded, I have no choice but to obey your stern will.

    Yet I stand ashamed of my shadow, and sitting, my very spirit trembles. Each night before the cold lamp, each dawn before the clear mirror, I am moved to tears that fall like rain, and my anxious perspiration soaks through my garments. Though I am honored to escape the dust of the world, I have twice defiled your household.

    I reverently consider that you, the Grand Commandant, possess such towering reputation, such eminent virtue, such illustrious achievement—your name clouds the nine provinces and your influence extends to ten thousand lands. All look to you for guidance, both scholars and warriors. The many provinces follow in your wake like horses following their leader's head. Yet as commandant of inspection tours, you must select talented persons worthy of their stations—to satisfy the expectations of the four quarters abroad and to command the authority of the realm within. Should I, tainted by your favor, occupy a position without merit, I fear only that I would invite the mockery of barbarians and the censure of the historians.

    In ancient times, the Han official Jin Ridi, though always near Emperor Wu, declined when the Emperor offered him greater favor, saying, "I am a foreign-born man. I fear only that the Xiongnu will despise the Han." Such is my petition today. The various officials have long made their public recommendation—all agreeing that lowly birth should not hinder advancement and that the foreign-born should not disturb the civilized order. Since coming to your service last year, I have had no other knowledge, only appearing modestly in the halls of your subordinates. Through their fortunate forgiveness and their joint recommendation when you visited the Eastern Pond last summer, I received your favor and suddenly your special regard.

    In my continued memorial, I have not merely followed your wishes—rather, I seek to preserve your reputation and maintain the proper order of your household. When you offered at year's end to establish me in a separate position, though I received your gracious assent, my concern only deepens. As the Six Strategies teaches: "Talent, great or small, is like a measuring vessel—it cannot hold stone. When full, it is discarded." Thus Confucius said of Meng Gongchuo, "He suffices as elder of Zhao and Wei, but cannot serve as chief minister of Teng or Xue."

    I offer my sincere plea: grant me the honor of relinquishing this post. If you do not cast me aside entirely but allow me to remain in humble dependence, I ask only that I be assigned to a position of surplus or receive a meager stipend. A single branch, a few grains of rice—enough to sustain my feathers. A bucket of water, a span of wave—enough for the fish's fins to rest easy. This is not performance of false modesty for reputation's sake, but truly the desire to measure my own capacity and avoid burdening your kindness.

    The Spring and Autumn records tell how the Duke of Qi wished to make Chen Jingzhong a minister. Jingzhong declined, saying, "As a sojourner, I am freed from punishment and relieved of burden. Already I have gained much. How dare I dishonor high office? I ask to die here." Yet when appointed as director of craftsmen, he lost no honor in his name. Thus ancient precedent shines clearly—when lowly sincerity is earnest, when one guards the Way, one is preserved from fault. Coming to your gate, one need not suffer contempt.

    I ask only that your favor remains like the mortar and pestle, that I may yet harbor clouds of aspiration. May the divining stalks and ceremonial pin remain in your thought, that they never fall to earth abandoned. I venture to trouble your authority with sentiments of desperate earnestness and trembling concern.
